Data Splitting Best Practice

	1.	Separate Data into Train and Test Sets First:
	•	Train Set (70-90%):
	•	Used for all aspects of model development, including:
	•	Data preparation (e.g., cleaning, imputation, scaling).
	•	Feature engineering and selection.
	•	Trying different algorithms (e.g., XGBoost vs. GAM).
	•	Hyperparameter tuning.
	•	Cross-validation is applied within this set to ensure robust evaluation during development.
	•	Test Set (10-30%):
	•	Held out entirely during development.
	•	Used only at the end for final model evaluation to provide an unbiased estimate of performance on unseen data.

	2.	Develop Exclusively on the Training Data:
	•	Perform all development activities within the training set or its cross-validation folds:
	•	Data Preparation: Fit imputation values, scalers, or encoders on the training set only. Apply these transformations to the validation and test sets without refitting.
	•	Feature Engineering and Selection: Test new features and selection strategies during cross-validation to avoid overfitting.
	•	Algorithm Comparison: Compare model algorithms (e.g., XGBoost vs. GAM) within cross-validation to choose the best-performing one.
	•	Business Metric Selection: Experiment with business metrics (e.g., RMSE, AUC, recall) using cross-validation.
	•	Validation Set (Optional):
	•	If needed, split part of the training set into a validation set to test the overall pipeline during development.
	•	Do not use the test set at this stage to preserve its integrity.

	3.	Use Cross-Validation for Tuning:
	•	During training, use k-fold cross-validation (e.g., 5-fold or 10-fold):
	•	Evaluate hyperparameters (e.g., learning_rate, max_depth).
	•	Test the impact of different preprocessing techniques, features, and algorithms.
	•	Average the metrics across folds for robust performance estimation.

	4.	Evaluate Only Once on the Test Set:
	•	After finalizing the model, train it on the entire training set (including validation, if used) using the best features, algorithm, and hyperparameters.
	•	Use the test set for final evaluation to provide a realistic estimate of model performance on unseen data.

Why This Approach is Important

	•	Preserves Test Set Integrity: Ensures the test set provides an unbiased performance estimate by keeping it untouched during development.
	•	Prevents Overfitting: Cross-validation prevents reliance on a single train/validation split, especially for small datasets.
	•	Supports Generalization: By isolating the test set, the model is better prepared to handle unseen, real-world data.

